replies.bodyText:
I could use Files.readString from NIO, instead of Resources.toString, but building a path is a nightmare. The possible result could be:
String program = Files.readString(Paths.get(getClass().getClassLoader().getResource(srcName).toURI()));

And I also need to care about URISyntaxException. That's why I decided to use Google library.

I got your point and I can accept your impl. Minor thing - bare in mind that Resources class is in @Beta according with doc, probably is not a problem for us!
@Beta
@GwtIncompatible
public final class Resources {
//...
}

